<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch2-First-Order" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>First-Order Differential Equations</title>

  <p>
    In this chapter, we shall study first-order ordinary differential equations
    that can be written in standard form
  </p>
  <md xml:id="eq-First-order-general" number="yes">
    y'=f(x,y).
  </md>
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- Section - Introduction to First-Order Differential Equations -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <section xml:id="sec-Intro-to-first-order">
    <title>Introduction to First-Order Differential Equations</title>

    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Particular, General, and Singular Solutions -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Part-general-singular">
      <title>Particular, General, and Singular Solutions</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-Particular-general-singular">
        <title>Particular, General, and Singular Solutions</title>

        <statement>
          <p>
            A function <m>y=y(x)</m> is said to be a <term>solution</term> of
            differential equation <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> on an
            interval <m>I</m> provided it is differentiable on <m>I</m> and
          </p>
          <md>
            y'(x)=f\left(x,y(x)\right)\text{ for all }x\in I
          </md>

          <p>
            A one-parameter family of solutions <m>y=y(x,c)</m> of differential
            equation <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> containing an
            arbitrary constant <m>c</m> is called a
            <term>general solution</term>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Any particular choice of a specific value for <m>c</m> yields a
            <term>particular solution</term>.
          </p>

          <p>
            A first-order differential equation may have both a general solution
            involving an arbitrary constant <m>c</m> and particular solutions
            that cannot be obtained from it by any choice of <m>c</m>.
            Such exceptional solutions are called
            <term>singular solutions</term> (see Examples
            <xref ref="example-Singular"/> in Section
            <xref ref="sec-Separable"/> ).
          </p>

          <p>
            To solve <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> is to find
            <em>all</em> of its solutions.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <note>
        <p>
          Since a differentiable function is necessarily continuous, every
          solution <m>y=y(x)</m> of <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> on an
          interval <m>I</m> must be continuous on <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </note>

      <p>
        For a first-order equation of the form
      </p>
      <md>
        y'=f(x),
      </md>

      <p>
        where <m>f(x)</m> is a continuous function on an interval <m>I</m>, a
        <term>general solution</term> on <m>I</m> is
      </p>
      <md>
        y=\int f(x)\,dx=F(x)+c\qquad (c\in \mathbb{R}),
      </md>

      <p>
        where <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f</m> on <m>I</m>.
        By the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (see, e.g., <xref ref="Stewart"/>
        ), we can set
      </p>
      <md>
        F(x):=\int_{x_0}^{x}f(t)\,dt,\quad x\in I,
      </md>

      <p>
        where <m>x_{0}</m> is a fixed point in <m>I</m>.
      </p>

      <example>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The one-parameter family <m>y=c</m> ( <m>c\in \mathbb{R}</m> ) is
              a general solution of the equation.
            </p>
            <md>
              y'=0
            </md>

            <p>
              on <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The one-parameter family <m>y=\ln|x|+c</m> (
              <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m> ) is the general solution of the equation.
            </p>
            <md>
              y'=\dfrac{1}{x}
            </md>

            <p>
              on each of the intervals <m>(-\infty,0)</m> and <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </example>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Particular, General, and Singular Solutions -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-IVP">
      <title>Initial Value Problems</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-Initial-value-problem">
        <title>Initial Value Problem</title>

        <statement>
          <p>
            A first-order differential equation
            <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> is often accompanied by a
            condition of the form:
          </p>
          <md>
            y(x_{0})=y_{0},
          </md>

          <p>
            where <m>x_{0}</m> and <m>y_{0}</m> are specified values.
            Such a condition is called an <term>initial condition</term> (IC)
            and such a problem
          </p>
          <md xml:id="eq-IVP" number="yes">
            y'=f(x,y),\ y(x_{0})=y_{0}
          </md>

          <p>
            is called an <term>initial value problem</term> (IVP).
          </p>

          <p>
            A solution of the initial value problem <xref ref="eq-IVP"/> is a
            function <m>y=y(x)</m> satisfying both the differential equation on
            some interval <m>I</m> containing <m>x_{0}</m> and the initial
            condition.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <p>
        One way to solve initial value problem <xref ref="eq-IVP"/> is to
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              first find the general solution <m>y=y(x,c)</m> of the equation,
              which, provided the differential equation is of the form
            </p>
            <md>
              y'=f(x),
            </md>

            <p>
              can be done via indefinite integration
            </p>
            <md>
              y=\int f(x)\,dx,
            </md>

            <p>
              and
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              then, plug <m>x = x_{0}</m> and <m>y = y_{0}</m> into the general
              solution, and solve for <m>c</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <example xml:id="example-IVP-reciprocal">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the initial value problem
          </p>
          <md>
            y'=\dfrac{1}{x},\ y(1)=0.
          </md>

          <p>
            <alert>Solution:</alert> Considering that the initial <m>x</m>-value
            1 is in the interval <m>(0,\infty)</m>, where <m>|x|=x</m>, we
            obtain the unique solution of the IVP from the general solution
            <m>y=\ln|x|+c=\ln x+c</m> of the equation on <m>(0,\infty)</m> by
            substituting the values <m>x=1</m> and <m>y=0</m> into it:
          </p>
          <md>
            0=\ln 1+c,
          </md>

          <p>
            which yields <m>c = 0</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Thus, the unique solution to the IVP on <m>(0,\infty)</m> is
          </p>

          <p>
            <md>
              \boxed{y=\ln x.}
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>

      <p>
        An alternative <term>definite-integral approach</term> to solving an
        initial value problem of the form
      </p>
      <md xml:id="eq-IVP-single-variable" number="yes">
        y'=f(x),\ y(x_{0})=y_{0},
      </md>

      <p>
        which bypasses finding the general solution of the differential
        equation, is based on the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus and, provided
        the function <m>f(x)</m> is continuous on an interval <m>I</m>
        containing <m>x_{0}</m>, gives the <em>unique</em> solution of the IVP
        by the formula
      </p>
      <md>
        y=y_{0}+\int_{x_0}^{x}f(t)\,dt.
      </md>

      <p>
        In the following two examples, we will compare the two approaches to
        solving initial value problem <xref ref="eq-IVP-single-variable"/>.
      </p>

      <example>
        <title>Indefinite Integral Approach</title>

        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the differential equation
          </p>
          <md>
            y'=x\sqrt{x^{2}+9},\ y(-4)=0
          </md>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            First, we find the general solution of the equation
          </p>
          <md>
            y= \int x \sqrt{x^{2} + 9}\, dx
          </md>

          <p>
            Using substitution ( <m>u = x^{2} + 9</m>, so <m>du = 2x \, dx</m>
            ), we obtain
          </p>
          <md>
            y= \frac{1}{3}(x^{2} + 9)^{\frac{3}{2}}+ C
          </md>

          <p>
            Next, we need to determine the value of <m>c</m> for which the
            solution we have obtained will satisfy the IVP.
          </p>

          <p>
            Substituting in the initial condition gives
          </p>
          <md>
            \dfrac{1}{3}\left((-4)^{2}+9\right)^{3/2}+c=0,
          </md>

          <p>
            which we solve to find <m>c=-\dfrac{125}{3}</m>.
            The unique solution is, therefore,
          </p>
          <md>
            \boxed{y = \dfrac{1}{3}(x^2+9)^{3/2}-\dfrac{125}{3},}
          </md>

          <p>
            or
          </p>
          <md>
            \boxed{y = \dfrac{1}{3}\left((x^2+9)^{3/2}-125\right).}
          </md>
        </solution>
      </example>

      <example>
        <title>Definite Integral Approach</title>

        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the differential equation
          </p>
          <md>
            y'=xe^{-x},\ y(0)=1.
          </md>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            The desired solution is given by the formula
          </p>
          <md>
            y=1+\int_{0}^{x}te^{-t}\,dt.
          </md>

          <p>
            Integrating by parts, with
          </p>
          <md>
            <mrow>u\amp =t,\amp du\amp =dt</mrow>
            <mrow>dv\amp =e^{-t}\;dt,\amp v\amp =-e^{-t},</mrow>
          </md>

          <p>
            we have:
          </p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\int_{0}^{x}te^{-t}\,dt\amp = \left[\left.-te^{-t}\right|_{0}^{x}+\int_{0}^{x} e^{-t}\,dt\right]</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp =\left[\left.-xe^{-x}-e^{-t}\right|_{0}^{x}\right] </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp =\left[-xe^{-x}-(e^{-x}-1)\right]</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp =-xe^{-x}-e^{-x}+1=-(x+1)e^{-x}+1.</mrow>
          </md>

          <p>
            Therefore, the solution is
          </p>
          <md>
            \boxed{y(x)=-(x+1)e^{-x}+2.}
          </md>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Exercises for Intro to First-Order Differential Equations -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Exercises for <xref ref="sec-Intro-to-first-order"/></title>

      <p>
        Find a general solution of the following equations.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle y' = xe^{-x^2}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}= 3x^{2}\sin(x^{3})</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}= 4e^{t} \cos(t)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        Solve the following initial value problems.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle y' = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{x+2}}, \ y(2)=-1</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle y' = (t^{2} + 2t + 1)e^{t}, \ y(0) = 2</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= \dfrac{\ln(x)}{x}, \ y(1) = 0 \quad (x &gt; 0)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- Section - Separable Differential Equations -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <section xml:id="sec-Separable">
    <title>Separable Differential Equations</title>

    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Motivating Example: Home Loan -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection xml:id="motivation-Home-loan">
      <title>Motivating Example: Home Loan</title>

      <p>
        Suppose you want to take out a 30-year loan to purchase a house.
        If interest rates are 4.75% and you know that you can afford at most
        $1,250 per month, you would like to determine the most expensive house
        that you can purchase in order pay off the loan on time.
        To do this, define <m>L(t)</m> as the amount that you owe after <m>t</m>
        years.
        Since you can afford $1,250 per month, your annual payments will be
        <m>\$1,250 \times 12 = \$15,000</m>.
        The balance due will gain 4.75% interest, so that amount added to the
        balance annually is <m>0.0475L</m>.
        Thus, the rate of change in the amount of money due is given by the
        difference between the amount the loan increases and the amount that you
        pay on the loan, or <m>\dfrac{dL}{dt}=0475L - 15000</m>.
        The initial condition is <m>L(30) = 0</m>, because you want the entire
        loan to be paid off by the end of the 30 years.
        This gives the initial value problem
      </p>
      <md xml:id="eq-Home-loan" number="yes">
        \frac{dL}{dt}= 0.0475L - 15000, \, L(30) = 0.
      </md>

      <p>
        This is a separable equation, as we will see momentarily (also a linear
        equation, as we will see in Section <xref ref="sec-Linear"/> ).
        The solution to <xref ref="eq-Home-loan"/> is
      </p>
      <md>
        L(t) = \frac{6000000}{19}\left(1 - e^{\frac{19}{400}t-\frac{57}{40}}\right).
      </md>

      <p>
        The size of the loan you should take is the amount you owe at the
        beginning, or <m>L(0)</m>, which is $239,839.43.
      </p>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Separable Differential Equations -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Definition and Examples</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-Separable">
        <title>Separable Differential Equation</title>

        <statement>
          <p>
            A first-order differential equation
          </p>
          <md>
            \dfrac{dy}{dx}=f(x,y),
          </md>

          <p>
            whose right-hand side can be factored into <m>g(x)h(y)</m>, i.e., it
            can written in the form
          </p>
          <md xml:id="eq-Seperable-form" number="yes">
            \dfrac{dy}{dx}=g(x)h(y),
          </md>

          <p>
            is called <term>separable</term>.
          </p>

          <p>
            There are two special cases of separable equations:
          </p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \frac{dy}{dx}\amp =g(x) \quad (h(y)=1),</mrow>
            <mrow> \frac{dy}{dx}\amp =h(y)\quad (g(x)=1) \qquad \text{(called an \emph{autonomous equation})}.</mrow>
          </md>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <example>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=x^{2}e^{-y}</m> is separable.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=\sin t^{2}</m> is separable.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The <term>exponential</term> differential equation
              <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}=kx</m> where <m>k\in \mathbb{R}</m> is separable
              (and autonomous).
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The <term>logistic</term> differential equation
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=ky\left(1-\dfrac{y}{N}\right)</m> where (
              <m>k, N &gt; 0 </m> are constants) is separable (and autonomous).
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\dfrac{\sqrt{y}}{xy+x+y+1}</m> is separable.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=y+x</m> is not separable.
              As we will see in Section <xref ref="sec-Linear"/>, this equation
              is also <term>linear</term>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=y^{3}+xy+5</m> is not separable.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </example>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Method of Separation of Variables -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Separation-of-variables">
      <title>Method of Separation of Variables</title>

      <p>
        Consider a separable differential equation
      </p>
      <md>
        \dfrac{dy}{dx}=g(x)h(y).
      </md>

      <p>
        Observe that, if there is such a <m>c\in \mathbb{R}</m> such that
        <m>h(c)=0</m>, then the constant function <m>y=c</m> is a so-called
        <term>equilibrium solution</term> of the equation.
        The method of separation of variables is used for solving these
        differential equations.
      </p>
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- Subsubsection - How Separation Works -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-How-separation-works">
        <title>How Separation of Variables Works</title>

        <p>
          The method of separation of variables works as follows:
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find all equilibrium solutions from the equation
            </p>
            <md>
              h(y)=0.
            </md>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Separate the variables:
            </p>
            <md>
              \frac{1}{h(y)}\, dy=g(x)\,dx.
            </md>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Integrate both sides:
            </p>
            <md>
              \int\frac{1}{h(y)}\,dy=\int g(x)\,dx.
            </md>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Solve the resulting equation for <m>y</m>, whenever possible,
              obtaining a general solution.
              The equilibrium solutions that are not included in this general
              solution give the singular solutions.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <example xml:id="example-Singular">
          <statement>
            <p>
              The separable differential equation
              <md>
                y'=y^{2}.
              </md>
              has a general solution of <m>y=\dfrac{1}{c-x}</m> (
              <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m> ) and the singular equilibrium solution
              <m>y=0</m> not included in the general solution.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </example>

        <remark>
          <p>
            If it is impossible (or impractical) to solve the resulting equation
            for <m>y</m>, the general solution is said to be an
            <term>implicit general solution</term>.
          </p>
        </remark>

        <example xml:id="example-Separable-worked-out">
          <title>Solving a Separable Differential Equation</title>

          <statement>
            <p>
              Solve the differential equation
              <md>
                \frac{dy}{dt}=\frac{2y+1}{t}.
              </md>
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              To solve this separable DE, we apply the method of separation of
              variables.
            </p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find the equilibrium solutions from the equation
                  <md>
                    2y+1=0.
                  </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                  Clearly, there is only one: <m>y=-\dfrac{1}{2}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Separate the variables:
                </p>
                <md>
                  \frac{1}{2y+1}dy=\frac{1}{t}dt\quad (y\neq -1/2)
                </md>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Integrate both sides:
                </p>
                <md>
                  <mrow> \int\frac{1}{2y+1}dy\amp =\int\frac{1}{t}dt,</mrow>
                  <mrow> \frac{1}{2}\ln|2y+1|\amp =\ln|t|+c\ (c\in \mathbb{R}).</mrow>
                </md>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Solve the resulting equation for <m>y</m>:
                </p>
                <md>
                  <mrow> \ln|2y+1|\amp =2\ln|t|+c\amp \amp(\text{where } c\in \mathbb{R}) </mrow>
                  <mrow> |2y+1|\amp =e^{2\ln|t|+c} \amp \amp\text{(exponentiate both sides)}</mrow>
                  <mrow> |2y+1|\amp =e^{c}\;t^{2} \amp \amp\text{(exponent rules)}</mrow>
                  <mrow> |2y+1|\amp =c_{1}\;t^{2} \amp \amp(\text{replace } c_{1}:=e^{c} &gt; 0)</mrow>
                  <mrow> 2y+1\amp =\pm c_{1}\;t^{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow> 2y+1\amp =c_{2}t^{2} \amp \amp(\text{ where }c_{2} := \pm c_{1} \neq 0 ) </mrow>
                  <mrow> y\amp =c_{2}\;t^{2}-\frac{1}{2} \amp \amp(\text{solve for }y)</mrow>
                </md>

                <p>
                  Renaming <m>c_{2}</m> to simply <m>c</m>, we obtain the
                  general solution
                </p>
                <md>
                  \boxed{y(x)=ct^2-\dfrac{1}{2}\qquad\text{where } c\in \mathbb{R}\text{ and }t\neq 0}
                </md>

                <p>
                  <em>Question:</em> What is the reason for the requirement that
                  <m>t\neq 0</m>?
                </p>

                <p>
                  Observe that the equilibrium solution <m>y=-\dfrac{1}{2}</m>
                  is attained when <m>c=0</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </example>
      </subsubsection>
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- Subsubsection - Why Separation of Variables Works -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <subsubsection>
        <title>Why Separation of Variables Works</title>

        <p>
          The method of separation of variables is based on the substitution
          rule for indefinite integrals <xref ref="Stewart"/>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Indeed, let <m>y=y(x)</m> be a nonequilibrium solution of a separable
          equation
          <md xml:id="eq-SDE" number="yes">
            \dfrac{dy}{dx}=g(x)h(y)
          </md>
          on an interval <m>I</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Then, for all <m>x\in I</m>,
          <md xml:id="eq-Why-separation-works" number="yes">
            y'(x)=g(x)h(y(x)).
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Dividing both sides of differential equation
          <xref ref="eq-Why-separation-works"/> by <m>h(y(x))</m> and
          integrating, we obtain
          <md>
            \int\frac{1}{h(y(x))}y'(x)\,dx=\int g(x)\,dx \text{ on }I.
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Using the substitution <m>y=y(x)</m>, we obtain
          <md xml:id="eq-INTE" number="yes">
            \int\frac{1}{h(y)}\,dy=\int g(x)\, dx.
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Thus, any nonequilibrium solution <m>y(x)</m> of differential equation
          <xref ref="eq-SDE"/> satisfies integral equation
          <xref ref="eq-INTE"/>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, a function <m>y=y(x)</m>, implicitly defined by integral
          equation <xref ref="eq-INTE"/> on the interval <m>I</m>, solves
          <xref ref="eq-SDE"/> on <m>I</m>.
          Indeed, differentiating <xref ref="eq-INTE"/> relative to <m>x</m> by
          the chain rule (considering <m>y=y(x)</m> ), we arrive at
          <xref ref="eq-Why-separation-works"/> for all <m>x\in I</m>.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Separable Exercises -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Exercises for Section <xref ref="sec-Separable"/></title>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine which of the following first order differential
              equations are separable.
            </p>

            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= 3x^{2}y</m>
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle y' = e^{2x+y}</m>
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= x^{2} + 2xy + y^{2}</m>
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \tan(x) y' = y^{2} + 1</m>
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= xy + x + y</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Apply the method of separation of variables to verify
              <xref ref="example-Singular"/>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        Find a general solution for each of the following equations.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle (x^{2} + 1)y' = y^{2} + 1</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle y' = 3x^{2}y^{2}</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \left(\frac{2y}{x}\right) \frac{dy}{dx}= 0 \quad (x \ne 0)</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \sin(y) y' = \cos(x)</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle y' = 3x^{2}e^{y}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        Solve the following initial value problems.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle y\frac{dy}{dx}= x^{2} + 1, \ y(0) = -2</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= \frac{y}{x}, \ y(1) = 1</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle x^{2} y' = y, \ y(1) = 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= xy + x + y + 1, \ y(0) = 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle x\dfrac{dy}{dx}-y = 2x^{2}y, \ y(1) = 1</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle y' = 2x(y^{2} + 1), \ y(\sqrt{\pi}) = 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle xy' = 2y\ln(x), \ y(1) = 2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- Section - Applications of Separable Equations -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <section xml:id="sepapp">
    <title>Applications of Separable Equations</title>

    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Radiocarbon Dating -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Radiocarbon Dating</title>
      <p>
        Carbon-14 is a radioactive isotope of carbon produced in the upper
        atmosphere by radiation from the sun.
        Plants absorb carbon dioxide from the air, and living organisms eat
        plants.
        The ratio of normal carbon (Carbon-12) to Carbon-14 in the air and
        living things is nearly constant.
        When a living creature dies, the Carbon-14 begins to decrease due to
        radioactive decay.
        By comparing the amounts of Carbon-12 and Carbon-14, the amount of
        Carbon-14 that has decayed can be determined.
      </p>
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- Subsubsubsection - Mathematical Model -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <subsubsection>
        <title>Mathematical Model</title>

        <p>
          Let <m>y(t) =</m> amount of Carbon-14 present at time <m>t</m> after
          death.
        </p>

        <p>
          The model of radioactive decay we'll use is:
          <md>
            y' = -ky\quad\text{where}\quad k&gt;0.
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          We need additional information to find <m>k</m>.
          For example, if we have the half-life of Carbon-14 (which is standard
          information for a radioactive isotope), we can determine <m>k</m>.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- Subsubsubsection - Sample Case -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <!-- ===================================================== -->
      <subsubsection>
        <title>Sample Case</title>

        <p>
          The half-life of Carbon-14 is approximately 5,730 years.
          Suppose remains have been found in which it is estimated that 30% of
          the original Carbon-14 is present.
          Estimate the age of the remains.
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Step 1:</em> Solve the IVP
          <md>
            y'=-ky, \ y(0)=y_{0}.
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Note:</em> We can also set <m>y(0) = 100</m> (for 100%) or
          <m>y(0) = 1</m> (for 100% in decimal form).
        </p>

        <p>
          By separation of variables, we see that the general solution is
          <md>
            y(t) = ce^{-kt}.
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Using the initial condition, <m>c = y_{0}</m>, so
          <md>
            y(t) = y_{0}e^{-kt}.
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Step 2:</em> Find <m>k</m>
        </p>

        <p>
          To find <m>k</m>, we will use the half-life of Carbon-14.
          Since the half-life is the amount of time for half of the sample to
          decay, we know that <m>y(5730)=\frac{1}{2}y_{0}.</m> Therefore,
          <md>
            <mrow> \frac{1}{2}y_{0}\amp = y_{0} e^{-k(5730)} </mrow>
            <mrow> \ln \frac{1}{2}\amp = -5730k </mrow>
            <mrow> k\amp = -\frac{\ln\frac{1}{2}}{5730}\approx 0.000121. </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Step 3:</em> Determine the age of the remains.
        </p>

        <p>
          At time <m>t_{\ast}</m> (the age), we have 30%of the original amount
          of Carbon-14, or <m>y(t_{\ast}) = 0.3y_{0}.</m> So, plugging this into
          our solution for <m>y(t)</m> will allow us to solve for the age of the
          remains.
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>0.3y_{0}\amp = y_{0} e^{-0.000121t_{\ast}} </mrow>
          <mrow>\ln 0.3\amp = -0.000121 t_{\ast}</mrow>
          <mrow> t_{\ast}\amp = -\frac{\ln 0.3}{0.000121}\approx 9,950 \text{ years}. </mrow>
        </md>
      </subsubsection>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Geometric Example -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Geometric Example</title>

      <p>
        Find the curve with slope <m>\displaystyle -\frac{x}{y}</m> through the
        point (0, 1).
      </p>

      <p>
        <em>Solution:</em> The differential equation
        <md>
          \frac{dy}{dx}= -\frac{x}{y}
        </md>
        modeling this problem has the implicit general solution
        <md>
          x^{2} + y^{2} = c.
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Substituting <m>x=0</m> and <m>y=1</m> into it, we arrive at
        <md>
          1^{2} + 0^{2}=c,
        </md>
        so <m>c=1</m>, and therefore, the desired curve is the unit circle
        <md>
          x^{2} + y^{2} = 1
        </md>.
      </p>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsubsubsection - Mixing Problem -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Mixing Problem</title>

      <p>
        A typical mixing problem is about the amount or concentration of a
        <em>solute</em> in a <em>solution</em> with certain flows of solutions
        with the same solute into and out of a container holding the solution.
      </p>

      <p>
        <em>Model:</em> Let <m>y(t)</m> be the amount of solute in the container
        at any time <m>t</m>.
        Then, we have that
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>
          rate of change in amount of solute = total solute inflow rate <m>-</m>
          total solute outlow rate
        </p>

        <p>
          (i.e., <m>y' = \mbox{rate in}- \mbox{rate out}</m> ).
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        <em>Note:</em> The total solute inflow rate is determined by summing the
        inflow rates from each source, and similarly for the total solute
        outflow rate.
      </p>

      <p>
        Each solute inflow rate is found by multiplying the rate at which fluid
        flows into the container by the concentration of solute:
      </p>

      <p>
        <md>
          \text{inflow rate}= \text{(rate of fluid inflow)}\cdot \text{(concentration of solute)}.
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Each solute outflow rate is found by multiplying the rate at which fluid
        flows out of the container by the concentration of solute in the
        container:
      </p>

      <p>
        <md>
          \text{outflow rate}=\left(\text{rate of fluid outflow}\right) \cdot \left(\frac{\text{amount of solute in container}}{\text{volume of solution in container}}\right).
        </md>
      </p>

      <note>
        <p>
          The resulting DE is a first-order linear equation regardless of
          whether the rates, concentrations, and volume are constant or
          variable.
          When all of the rates, concentrations, and volume are constant, this
          equation is also separable (and even autonomous).
        </p>
      </note>

      <example>
        <title>Mixing Problem with Constant Volume</title>

        <p>
          A tank contains <m>1000</m> L of pure water.
          A brine containing <m>0.05</m> kg/L of salt enters the tank at a
          constant rate of <m>5</m> L/min.
          A brine containing <m>0.04</m> kg/L of salt enters the tank at a
          constant rate of <m>10</m> L/min.
          The solution is kept thoroughly mixed and drains from the tank at a
          constant rate of <m>15</m> L/min.
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Set up an initial value problem describing how the amount of salt
              in the tank changes over time.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the amount of salt in the tank after <m>t</m> min.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <figure xml:id="fig-mix1">
          <caption>Mixing Problem with Constant Volume</caption>
          <image source="mixconst1.jpg" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
              Image of cylindrical tank with two input sources and one output
              drain.
            </shortdescription>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>y(t)</m> be the amount of salt in the tank (kg) after
                  <m>t</m> min.
                </p>

                <p>
                  The rate of change of the amount of salt in the tank
                  <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}</m> (kg/min) consists of the two components:
                </p>

                <p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        the inflow rate of salt entering the tank, which
                        consists of the sum of the rates coming from the two
                        sources
                      </p>
                      <md>
                        <mrow> \text{rate in}\amp = 5 \, \frac{\text{L}}{\text{min}}\cdot 0.05 \, \frac{\text{kg}}{\text{L}}+ 10 \, \frac{\text{L}}{\text{min}}\cdot 0.04 \, \frac{\text{kg}}{\text{L}} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 0.65\ \text{ kg/min}.</mrow>
                      </md>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        the outflow rate of salt leaving the tank:
                      </p>
                      <md>
                        \text{rate out}= 15 \frac{\text{L}}{\text{min}}\cdot\dfrac{y \text{ kg}}{1000 \text{ L}}= 0.015y\ \text{ kg/min}.
                      </md>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </p>

                <p>
                  Since initially there was no salt in the tank ( <m>y(0)=0</m>
                  ), we obtain at the following IVP model for the mixing
                  problem:
                </p>
                <md>
                  \dfrac{dy}{dt}=0.65-0.015y,\ y(0)=0.
                </md>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The DE is separable, and more precisely, it is autonomous.
                  Applying the method of separation of variables, we have:
                </p>

                <p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        The equilibrium solution is
                        <m>y=\dfrac{0.65}{0.015}</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Separating the variables, we obtain
                      </p>
                      <md>
                        <mrow> \dfrac{1}{0.65-0.015y}\,dy\amp = 1\,dt </mrow>
                        <mrow> \int\dfrac{1}{0.65-0.015y}\,dy\amp =\int 1\,dt </mrow>
                        <mrow> \dfrac{1}{-0.015}\ln|0.65-0.015y|\amp = t+c_{1} \quad (c_{1} \in \R). </mrow>
                      </md>

                      <p>
                        Now we solve for <m>y</m>:
                      </p>
                      <md>
                        <mrow> \ln|0.015y-0.65|\amp = -0.015t+c \quad (c \in \R) </mrow>
                        <mrow> y(t)\amp = \frac{0.65}{0.015}+ce^{-0.015t}\quad (c \in \R) </mrow>
                      </md>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Find <m>c</m>: Using the initial condition
                        <m>y(0)=0</m>, we have
                        <md>
                          0 = \frac{0.65}{0.015}+ c,
                        </md>
                        so <m>c=-\dfrac{0.65}{0.015}</m> and the solution of the
                        problem is
                        <md>
                          \boxed{y(t) =\frac{0.65}{0.015}-\frac{0.65}{0.015}e^{-0.015t}.}
                        </md>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>

            <figure xml:id="fig-mix2">
              <caption>The Graph of <m>y</m> ( <m>y(0)=0</m> )</caption>
              <image source="mixconst2.jpg" width="80%"/>
              <shortdescription>
                Curve that starts at origin and increases towards a horizontal
                asymptote at <m>y=43</m>.
              </shortdescription>
            </figure>
            Note that <m> y </m> increasingly tends to the equilibrium
            <m> \dfrac{0.65}{0.015}\approx 43 </m> kg as <m> t\to \infty </m>,
            but never attains it.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Newton's Law of Cooling/Heating -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Newton's Law of Cooling/Heating</title>

      <p>
        Newton's Law of Cooling/Heating states that the rate of change of the
        temperature of an object, <m>T</m>, is proportional to the difference
        between the ambient temperature of the surroundings, <m>A</m>, and
        <m>T</m>:
        <md xml:id="eq-cool" number="yes">
          \dfrac{dT}{dt}= k(A - T),
        </md>
        where <m>k &gt; 0</m> is the constant of proportionality.
      </p>

      <example xml:id="ex-newt">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider a tray of cookies removed from the oven at
            350<m>^{\circ}</m> F and placed in a room with a temperature of
            72<m>^{\circ}</m> F.
            If the cookies are at 240<m>^{\circ}</m> F after 10 minutes, how
            long will it take for them to cool to 80<m>^{\circ}</m> F?
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            The IVP modeling this situation is given by applying equation
            <xref ref="eq-cool"/>:
          </p>
          <md>
            \dfrac{dT}{dt}= k(72 - T), \ T(0) = 350.
          </md>

          <p>
            We will apply the method of separation of variables.
            Separating variables gives
            <md>
              \dfrac{1}{72-T}\, dT = k \, dt.
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Integrate both sides and solve for <m>T</m>:
          </p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \int \dfrac{1}{72-T}\, dT\amp = \int k \, dt </mrow>
            <mrow> -\ln|72 - T|\amp = kt + c </mrow>
            <mrow> \ln|72 - T|\amp = -kt + c </mrow>
            <mrow> 72 - T\amp = ce^{-kt} </mrow>
            <mrow> T\amp = 72 + ce^{-kt}. </mrow>
          </md>

          <p>
            We next need to determine <m>c</m> and <m>k</m>.
            We first find <m>c</m> using the initial condition:
            <md>
              350 = T(0) = 72 + c, \text{ so }c = 278.
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            So, we have
            <md>
              T = 72 + 278e^{-kt}.
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Now we use the fact (given in the problem) that <m>T(10) = 240</m>
            to find <m>k</m>.
          </p>
          <md>
            <mrow> 240 \amp = 72 + 278e^{-10k} </mrow>
            <mrow> 168 \amp = 278 e^{-10k} </mrow>
            <mrow> e^{-10k} \amp = \dfrac{168}{278}= \dfrac{84}{139}. </mrow>
          </md>

          <p>
            Then take the natural log of both sides and solve for <m>k</m>:
          </p>
          <md>
            <mrow> -10k\amp = \ln\left( \dfrac{84}{139}\right) </mrow>
            <mrow> k\amp = -\frac{1}{10}\ln\left( \dfrac{84}{139}\right) \approx 0.053657. </mrow>
          </md>

          <p>
            Let <m>t_{s}</m> denote the time at which the temperature of the
            cookies is 80<m>^{\circ}</m> F.
            Then
          </p>

          <p>
            <md>
              80 = 72 + 278e^{-0.053657 t_s}.
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Solving for <m>t_{s}</m> gives us <m>t_{s} = 70.45</m>.
            So, the cookies will be at 80<m>^{\circ}</m> F after 70.45 minutes,
            or after 1 hour, 10 minutes, and 27 seconds.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </subsection>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Subsection - Exercises for Applications of Separable Equations -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <subsection>
      <title>Exercises for Section <xref ref="sepapp"/></title>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Verify the solution to the Geometric Application problem.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the equation of the curve with slope <m>\dfrac{x}{y}</m>
              through the point <m>(0, 2)</m>.
              What type of curve is this?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the equation of the curve with slope <m>\dfrac{y}{x}</m>
              through the point <m>(1, 0)</m>.
              What type of curve is this?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              (Drug Elimination) The amount <m>y(t)</m> of a certain drug in the
              bloodstream as a function of time <m>t</m> declining at a rate
              proportional to the current excess amount relative to the natural
              level of the drug (typically 0) is modeled by the differential
              equation
            </p>
            <md>
              \frac{dy}{dt}= -r y,
            </md>

            <p>
              where <m>r &gt; 0</m>.
              Suppose that after 2 hours, half of the initial amount of the drug
              is left in the patient's system (i.e., <m>y(2) = 0.5y(0)</m> ).
              Find <m>y(t)</m> assuming that initially, the patient is given 250
              mg of the drug (i.e., <m>y(0) = 250</m> ).
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              (Radiocarbon Dating) The half-life of Carbon-14 is approximately
              5,730 years.
              Suppose remains have been found in which it is estimated that
              65%of the original Carbon-14 has decayed.
              Estimate the age of the remains.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              (Population Model) A new species of animal has just been
              discovered.
              The rate of change in the size of its population was found to be
              proportional to the square root of its current size.
            </p>

            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Formulate a mathematical model describing the population
                    size <m>P(t)</m> of this new species over time.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    If the initial population is <m>100</m> animals and, after 2
                    months, the population has grown to 400 animals, determine
                    the size of the population at any time <m>t</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    How long before the population has grown to 1000 animals?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              (Logistic Population Model) A population model that takes into
              account the fact that, as a population grows in size its rate of
              change decreases, is the <em>logistic model</em>.
              Given a population of size <m>P(t)</m>, the logistic model is
              defined by
            </p>

            <p>
              <md>
                \dfrac{dP}{dt}= rP\left(1 - \dfrac{P}{K}\right),
              </md>
            </p>

            <p>
              where <m>r</m> is the intrinsic growth rate of the population in a
              given area (the growth rate in the absence of any restrictions)
              and <m>K</m> is the carrying capacity of the area (the maximum
              population that can be supported).
            </p>

            <p>
              If <m>r = 2</m> per year and <m>K = 10000</m>, use the logistic
              equation to determine the population size at any time of a species
              with an initial population of 1000.
            </p>

            <p>
              <em>Hint: You will need to use partial fractions to evaluate the integral on the left-hand side.</em>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>
</chapter>